node.text:
⚠️Severe fungal infection after a dental procedure!⚠️
.
Fungal infections like the one shown in these photos are very rare, but life-threatening conditions. 
.
In this case, the patient was immunocompromised and also suffered from uncontrolled diabetes. 
.
The fungal infection developed a few weeks after the patient had undergone a tooth extraction. After diagnosis, the patient underwent prolonged combined systemic antifungal treatment. Then extensive surgical debridement was performed, followed by reconstruction with a pedicled myocutaneous flap. Luckily the patient did recover from the infection. 
.
Second photo breakdown: 
(A) Intra-operative view after extensive surgical debridement. 
(B) Intra-operative view after reconstruction. 
(C) 2 weeks after operation. 
(D) 16 months after operation.

node.text:
What is that?!👀🤯
.
.
.
.
What you’re seeing in this video is a patient removing subcutaneous sutures from the lower eyelid. 
.
Unique challenges are associated with eyelid skin repair after a traumatic injury or cosmetic procedure. This means that dissolvable suturing techniques may be less useful in locations near the eye. 
.
The skin around the eye is very thin, with a near absence of subcutaneous fat in some areas. This provides only minimal tissue volume to aid in absorbable suture material breakdown, potentially increasing the chance of suture spitting or suture abscess formation. 
Many times, continuous subcutaneous sutures (as seen being removed in this video) are used around the eye instead of dissolvable sutures.
.
#eye #wow #medical #educational #hospital #emergencymedicine #doctor #nursing #ems #emt #paramedic #occular #eyelidsurgery

node.text:
⚠️Bladder stone removal in the late 1800s!⚠️
Bladder stones would be removed by DRIVING A NAIL THROUGH THE PENIS and then using a hammer to break the stone apart until it was small enough to pass through his urethra!
Imagine how desperate you would have to be to resort to these measures.
.
Lithotomy (pictured here) to remove stones would have been done WITHOUT anesthetic before 1846. 
.
The surgeon would pass a curved metal tube up the patient’s penis and into the bladder. He then slid a finger into the man’s rectum, feeling for the stone. 
.
Once he had located it, his assistant removed the metal tube and replaced it with a wooden staff, which acted as a guide so the surgeon wouldn’t fatally rupture the patient’s rectum or intestines as he began cutting deep into the bladder. 
.
When the staff was in place, the surgeon cut diagonally through the fibrous muscle of the scrotum until he reached the wooden staff. Next, he used the probe to widen the hole, ripping open the prostate gland in the process. At this point, he removed the wooden staff and used forceps to extract the stone from the bladder.
Credit: @drlindseyfitzharris

node.text:
C-section birth 👶🏼
In this AMAZING video you can see a baby entering the world by cesarean section (C-section) with the amniotic sac intact! This is known as an en-caul birth! 
.
Only about 1 in 80,000 births are en-caul!
.
An en-cal birth is when a baby is born still encased in the protective amniotic sac. Doctors manually pierce the membrane causing it to burst and remove the baby from the sac.
.
#childbirth #obstetrics #amnioticsac #membrane #medical #hospital #doctor #nurse #birth #laboranddelivery  #csection

Doctor drills his own leg with IO needle!💉🦴

.

You can follow Larry Mellick’s YouTube channel at https://m.youtube.com/user/lmellick

node.text:
HUGE BUG in man’s lip! 🐛 
.
This video shows the larvae of a botfly being removed from the upper lip of a man’s mouth! 
.
The botfly (mainly located in South America) is one of the few species who incubates it’s larvae on humans. 🤢
.
When this happens, a botfly latches onto a mosquito and attaches their eggs to the mosquitoes stomach. 
Then, when the mosquito lands on a human's skin, the botfly eggs burrow into the tiny wound of the mosquito bite, and the eggs then turn into larvae. 
.
If not removed like in this video, the larvae will fully grow and then dig their way out from underneath the person’s skin and fly away.
